Method Detail

getLiteral

java.lang.String getLiteral()
Returns the literal.

For the number, character or string literals the appropriate literal string will be returned. For the literal types LiteralType.TRUE , LiteralType.FALSE and LiteralType.NULL this method returns "true", "false" and "null", respectively.

Returns:
The literal.

setLiteral

java.lang.String setLiteral(java.lang.String pLiteral)
                            throws JSourceObjectizerException
Changes this to become a Literal object representing a literal stated as string.

Literals like numbers, boolean values, the null literal, characters and so on can be stated as expected, i.e. like

  • "123" (an integer)
  • "true" (a boolean literal)
  • "null" (the null literal)
  • "'a'" (the character literal a)
  • "'\''" (the character literal ')
For string literals it must be considered that they must be stated including the quotation marks that belong to the string literal. Examples are
  • "\"\"" (the empty string)
  • "\"anyString\"" (a simple non-empty string)
  • "\"with \\\" character\"" (a string containing one escaped '"' character)

Parameters:
pLiteral - The new literal stated as string.
Returns:
The old literal.
Throws:
JSourceObjectizerException - if the given literal isn't a valid literal; note that the passed literal string must be parsable by the unmarshaller.
See Also:
setLiteralChecked(String)

setLiteralChecked

java.lang.String setLiteralChecked(java.lang.String pLiteral)
Changes this to become a Literal object representing a literal stated as string.

Calling this method equals to a setLiteral(String) call with the exception that this method doesn't throw an exception if the given literal is invalid, i.e. not parsable. In such cases this method just returns null.

Literals like numbers, boolean values, the null literal, characters and so on can be stated as expected, i.e. like

  • "123" (an integer)
  • "true" (a boolean literal)
  • "null" (the null literal)
  • "'a'" (the character literal a)
  • "'\''" (the character literal ')
For string literals it must be considered that they must be stated including the quotation marks that belong to the string literal. Examples are
  • "\"\"" (the empty string)
  • "\"anyString\"" (a simple non-empty string)
  • "\"with \\\" character\"" (a string containing one escaped '"' character)

Parameters:
pLiteral - The new literal stated as string.
Returns:
The old literal or null if the passed literal is invalid, i.e. not parsable.
See Also:
setLiteral(String)
